# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: toxicology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] The liver plays a central role in transforming and clearing chemicals and is susceptible to the toxicity from these agents.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Certain medicinal agents when taken in overdoses (e.g. paracetamol, sometimes called acetaminophen), and sometimes even when introduced within therapeutic ranges (e.g. halothane), may injure the organ.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Other chemical agents, such as those used in laboratories and industries, natural chemicals (e.g., alpha-amanitin), and herbal remedies (two prominent examples being kava, though the causal mechanism is unknown, and comfrey, through pyrrolizidine alkaloid content) can also induce hepatotoxicity.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Chemicals that cause liver injury are called hepatotoxins.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] More than 900 drugs have been implicated in causing liver injury (see LiverTox, external link, below) and it is the most common reason for a drug to be withdrawn from the market.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Hepatotoxicity and drug-induced liver injury also account for a substantial number of compound failures, highlighting the need for toxicity prediction models (e.g.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] DTI), and drug screening assays, such as stem cell-derived hepatocyte-like cells, that are capable of detecting toxicity early in the drug development process.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Chemicals often cause subclinical injury to the liver, which manifests only as abnormal liver enzyme tests.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Drug-induced liver injury is responsible for 5% of all hospital admissions and 50% of all acute liver failures.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Adverse drug reactions are classified as type A (intrinsic or pharmacological) or type B (idiosyncratic).
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Type A drug reaction accounts for 80% of all toxicities.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Drugs or toxins that have a pharmacological (type A) hepatotoxicity are those that have *predictable* dose-response curves (higher concentrations cause more liver damage) and well characterized mechanisms of toxicity, such as directly damaging liver tissue or blocking a metabolic process.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] As in the case of paracetamol overdose, this type of injury occurs shortly after some threshold for toxicity is reached.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Carbon tetrachloride is commonly used to induce acute type A liver injury in animal models.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Idiosyncratic (type B) injury occurs without warning, when agents cause *non-predictable* hepatotoxicity in susceptible individuals, which is not related to dose and has a variable latency period.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] This type of injury does not have a clear dose-response nor temporal relationship, and most often does not have predictive models.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Idiosyncratic hepatotoxicity has led to the withdrawal of several drugs from market even after rigorous clinical testing as part of the FDA approval process; Troglitazone (Rezulin) and trovafloxacin (Trovan) are two prime examples of idiosyncratic hepatotoxins pulled from market.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] The herb kava has caused a number of cases of idiosyncratic liver injury, ranging everywhere from asymptomatic to fatal.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Oral use of the antifungal ketoconazole has been associated with hepatic toxicity, including some fatalities; however, such effects appear to be limited to doses taken over a period longer than 7 days.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Paracetamol also known as acetaminophen, and by the brand names of Tylenol and Panadol, is usually well-tolerated in prescribed dose, but overdose is the most common cause of drug-induced liver disease and acute liver failure worldwide.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Damage to the liver is not due to the drug itself but to a toxic metabolite (*N*-acetyl-*p*-benzoquinone imine (NAPQI)) produced by cytochrome P-450 enzymes in the liver.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] In normal circumstances, this metabolite is detoxified by conjugating with glutathione in phase 2 reaction.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] In an overdose, a large amount of NAPQI is generated, which overwhelms the detoxification process and leads to liver cell damage.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Nitric oxide also plays a role in inducing toxicity.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] The risk of liver injury is influenced by several factors including the dose ingested, concurrent alcohol or other drug intake, interval between ingestion and antidote, etc.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] The dose toxic to the liver is quite variable from person to person and is often thought to be lower in chronic alcoholics.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Measurement of blood level is important in assessing prognosis, higher levels predicting a worse prognosis.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Administration of Acetylcysteine, a precursor of glutathione, can limit the severity of the liver damage by capturing the toxic NAPQI.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Those that develop acute liver failure can still recover spontaneously, but may require transplantation if poor prognostic signs such as encephalopathy or coagulopathy is present (see King's College Criteria).
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Although individual analgesics rarely induce liver damage due to their widespread use, NSAIDs have emerged as a major group of drugs exhibiting hepatotoxicity.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Both dose-dependent and idiosyncratic reactions have been documented.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Aspirin and phenylbutazone are associated with intrinsic hepatotoxicity; idiosyncratic reaction has been associated with ibuprofen, sulindac, phenylbutazone, piroxicam, diclofenac and indomethacin.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Glucocorticoids are so named due to their effect on the carbohydrate mechanism.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] They promote glycogen storage in the liver.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] An enlarged liver is a rare side-effect of long-term steroid use in children.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] The classical effect of prolonged use both in adult and paediatric population is steatosis.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Isoniazide (INH) is one of the most commonly used drugs for tuberculosis; it is associated with mild elevation of liver enzymes in up to 20% of patients and severe hepatotoxicity in 1-2% of patients.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] There are also cases where other hydrazine derivative drugs, such as the MAOI antidepressant iproniazid, are associated with liver damage.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Phenelzine has been associated with abnormal liver tests.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Toxic effects can develop from antibiotics, such as amoxicillin/clavulanic acid.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Examples include alpha-Amanitin containing mushrooms, kava, and aflatoxin producing molds.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Pyrrolizidine alkaloids, which occur in some plants, can be toxic.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Green tea extract is a growing cause of liver failure due to its inclusion in more products.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Examples include: Ackee fruit, Bajiaolian, Camphor, Copaltra, Cycasin, Garcinia, Kava leaves, pyrrolizidine alkaloids, Horse chestnut leaves, Valerian, Comfrey.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Chinese herbal remedies: Jin Bu Huan, Ephedra, Shou Wu Pian, Bai Xian Pi.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Examples include arsenic, carbon tetrachloride, and vinyl chloride.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Drugs continue to be taken off the market due to late discovery of hepatotoxicity.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Due to its unique metabolism and close relationship with the gastrointestinal tract, the liver is susceptible to injury from drugs and other substances.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] 75% of blood coming to the liver arrives directly from gastrointestinal organs and the spleen via portal veins that bring drugs and xenobiotics in near-undiluted form.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Several mechanisms are responsible for either inducing hepatic injury or worsening the damage process.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Many chemicals damage mitochondria, an intracellular organelle that produces energy.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Its dysfunction releases excessive amount of oxidants that, in turn, injure hepatic cells.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Activation of some enzymes in the cytochrome P-450 system such as CYP2E1 also lead to oxidative stress.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Injury to hepatocyte and bile duct cells lead to accumulation of bile acid inside the liver.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Non-parenchymal cells such as Kupffer cells, collagen-producing stellate cells, and leukocytes (i.e. neutrophil and monocyte) also have a role in the mechanism.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] The human body subjects most, but not all, compounds to various chemical processes (i.e. metabolism) to make them suitable for elimination.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] This involves chemical transformations to (a) reduce fat solubility and (b) to change biological activity.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] The central role played by liver in the clearance and transformation of chemicals makes it susceptible to drug-induced injury.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Drug metabolism is usually divided into two phases: *phase 1* and *phase 2*.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Phase 1 reaction is generally speaking to prepare a drug for phase 2.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] However, many compounds can be metabolized by phase 2 directly or be excreted without any phase 2 reactions occurring.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Phase 1 reaction involves oxidation, reduction, hydrolysis, hydration and many other rare chemical reactions.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] These processes tend to increase water solubility of the drug and can generate metabolites that are more chemically active and/or potentially toxic.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Most of phase 2 reactions take place in cytosol and involve conjugation with endogenous compounds via transferase enzymes.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Phase 1 are typically more suitable for elimination.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] A group of enzymes located in the endoplasmic reticulum, known as cytochrome P-450, is the most important family of metabolizing enzymes in the liver.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Cytochrome P-450 is not a single enzyme, but rather consists of a closely related family of 50 isoforms; six of them metabolize 90% of drugs.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] There is a tremendous diversity of individual P-450 gene products, and this heterogeneity allows the liver to perform oxidation on a vast array of chemicals (including most drugs) in phase 1.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Each of the P-450 proteins is unique and accounts (to some extent) for the variation in drug metabolism between individuals.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Genetic variations (polymorphism) in P-450 metabolism should be considered when patients exhibit unusual sensitivity or resistance to drug effects at normal doses.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Such polymorphism is also responsible for variable drug response among patients of differing ethnic backgrounds.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Many substances can influence the P-450 enzyme mechanism.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Drugs interact with the enzyme family in several ways.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Drugs that modify cytochrome P-450 enzyme are referred to as either inhibitors or inducers.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Enzyme inhibitors block the metabolic activity of one or several P-450 enzymes.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] On the other hand, inducers increase P-450 activity by increasing enzyme production, or, in the case of CYP2E1, preventing degradation in the proteasome.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] There is usually a delay before enzyme activity increases.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Some drugs may share the same P-450 specificity and thus competitively block their biotransformation.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] This may lead to accumulation of drugs metabolized by the enzyme.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] This type of drug interaction may also reduce the rate of generation of toxic metabolites.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Chemicals produce a wide variety of clinical and pathological hepatic injury.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Biochemical markers (e.g. alanine transferase, alkaline phosphatase and bilirubin) are often used to indicate liver damage.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Liver injury is defined as a rise in either (a) ALT level more than three times of upper limit of normal (ULN), (b) ALP level more than twice ULN, or (c) total bilirubin level more than twice ULN when associated with increased ALT or ALP.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Liver damage is further characterized into hepatocellular (predominantly initial Alanine transferase elevation) and cholestatic (initial alkaline phosphatase rise) types.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] However they are not mutually exclusive and mixed types of injuries are often encountered.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Specific histo-pathological patterns of liver injury from drug-induced damage are discussed below.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] This is the most common type of drug-induced liver cell necrosis where the injury is largely confined to a particular zone of the liver lobule.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] It may manifest as a very high level of ALT and severe disturbance of liver function leading to acute liver failure.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] In this pattern, hepatocellular necrosis is associated with infiltration of inflammatory cells.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] There can be three types of drug-induced hepatitis.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] (A) viral hepatitis is the most common, where histological features are similar to acute viral hepatitis.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] (B) in focal or non-specific hepatitis, scattered foci of cell necrosis may accompany lymphocytic infiltration.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] (C) chronic hepatitis is very similar to autoimmune hepatitis clinically, serologically, and histologically.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Liver injury leads to impairment of bile flow and cases are predominated by itching and jaundice.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Histology may show inflammation (cholestatic hepatitis) or it can be bland (without any parenchymal inflammation).
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] On rare occasions, it can produce features similar to primary biliary cirrhosis due to progressive destruction of small bile ducts (vanishing duct syndrome).
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Hepatotoxicity may manifest as triglyceride accumulation, which leads to either small-droplet (microvesicular) or large-droplet (macrovesicular) fatty liver.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Drug-induced hepatic granulomas are usually associated with granulomas in other tissues and patients typically have features of systemic vasculitis and hypersensitivity.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] More than 50 drugs have been implicated.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] These result from injury to the vascular endothelium.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Neoplasms have been described with prolonged exposure to some medications or toxins.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Hepatocellular carcinoma, angiosarcoma, and liver adenomas are the ones usually reported.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] This remains a challenge in clinical practice due to a lack of reliable markers.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Many other conditions lead to similar clinical as well as pathological pictures.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] To diagnose hepatotoxicity, a causal relationship between the use of the toxin or drug and subsequent liver damage has to be established, but might be difficult, especially when idiosyncratic reaction is suspected.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Simultaneous use of multiple drugs may add to the complexity.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] As in acetaminophen toxicity, well established, dose-dependent, pharmacological hepatotoxicity is easier to spot.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Several clinical scales such as CIOMS/RUCAM scale and Maria and Victorino criteria have been proposed to establish causal relationship between offending drug and liver damage.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] CIOMS/RUCAM scale involves a scoring system that categorizes the suspicion into "definite or highly probable" (score > 8), "probable" (score 6–8), "possible" (score 3–5), "unlikely" (score 1–2) and "excluded" (score ≤ 0).
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] In clinical practice, physicians put more emphasis on the presence or absence of similarity between the biochemical profile of the patient and known biochemical profile of the suspected toxicity (e.g., cholestatic damage in amoxycillin-clauvonic acid ).
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] In most cases, liver function will return to normal if the offending drug is stopped early.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Additionally, the patient may require supportive treatment.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] In acetaminophen toxicity, however, the initial insult can be fatal.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Fulminant hepatic failure from drug-induced hepatotoxicity may require liver transplantation.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] In the past, glucocorticoids in allergic features and ursodeoxycholic acid in cholestatic cases had been used, but there is no good evidence to support their effectiveness.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] An elevation in serum bilirubin level of more than 2 times ULN with associated transaminase rise indicates severe hepatotoxicity and is likely to lead to mortality in 10% to 15% of patients, especially if the offending drug is not stopped (Hy's Law).
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] This is because it requires significant damage to the liver to impair bilirubin excretion, hence minor impairment (in the absence of biliary obstruction or Gilbert syndrome) would not lead to jaundice.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] Other poor predictors of outcome are old age, female sex, high AST.
[src:toxicology/hepatotoxicity] The following therapeutic drugs were withdrawn from the market primarily because of hepatotoxicity: Troglitazone, bromfenac, trovafloxacin, ebrotidine, nimesulide, nefazodone, ximelagatran and pemoline.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] In toxicology, the **median lethal dose**, **LD50** (abbreviation for "lethal dose, 50%"), **LC50** (lethal concentration, 50%) or **LCt50** is a toxic unit that measures the lethal dose of a given substance.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The value of LD50 for a substance is the dose required to kill half the members of a tested population after a specified test duration.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] LD50 figures are frequently used as a general indicator of a substance's acute toxicity.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] A lower LD50 is indicative of higher toxicity.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The term LD50 is generally attributed to John William Trevan.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The term **semilethal dose** is occasionally used in the same sense, in particular with translations of foreign language text, but can also refer to a sublethal dose.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] LD50 is usually determined by tests on animals such as laboratory mice.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Food and Drug Administration approved alternative methods to LD50 for testing the cosmetic drug botox without animal tests.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The LD50 is usually expressed as the mass of substance administered per unit mass of test subject, typically as milligrams of substance per kilogram of body mass, sometimes also stated as nanograms (suitable for botulinum toxin), micrograms, or grams (suitable for paracetamol) per kilogram.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Stating it this way allows the relative toxicity of different substances to be compared and normalizes for the variation in the size of the animals exposed (although toxicity does not always scale simply with body mass).
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] For substances in the environment, such as poisonous vapors or substances in water that are toxic to fish, the concentration in the environment (per cubic metre or per litre) is used, giving a value of LC50.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] But in this case, the exposure time is important (see below).
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The choice of 50% lethality as a benchmark avoids the potential for ambiguity of making measurements in the extremes and reduces the amount of testing required.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] However, this also means that LD50 is not the lethal dose for all subjects; some may be killed by much less, while others survive doses far higher than the LD50.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Measures such as "LD1" and "LD99" (dosage required to kill 1% or 99%, respectively, of the test population) are occasionally used for specific purposes.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Lethal dosage often varies depending on the method of administration; for instance, many substances are less toxic when administered orally than when intravenously administered.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The related quantities LD50/30 or LD50/60 are used to refer to a dose that without treatment will be lethal to 50% of the population within (respectively) 30 or 60 days.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] These measures are used more commonly within radiation health physics, for ionizing radiation, as survival beyond 60 days usually results in recovery.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] A comparable measurement is LCt50, which relates to lethal dosage from exposure, where C is concentration and t is time.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] It is often expressed in terms of mg-min/m3.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] ICt50 is the dose that will cause incapacitation rather than death.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] These measures are commonly used to indicate the comparative efficacy of chemical warfare agents, and dosages are typically qualified by rates of breathing (e.g., resting = 10 L/min) for inhalation, or degree of clothing for skin penetration.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The concept of Ct was first proposed by Fritz Haber and is sometimes referred to as Haber's law, which assumes that exposure to 1 minute of 100 mg/m3 is equivalent to 10 minutes of 10 mg/m3 (1 × 100 = 100, as does 10 × 10 = 100).
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Some chemicals, such as hydrogen cyanide, are rapidly detoxified by the human body, and do not follow Haber's law.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] In these cases, the lethal concentration may be given simply as LC50 and qualified by a duration of exposure (e.g., 10 minutes).
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The material safety data sheets for toxic substances frequently use this form of the term even if the substance does follow Haber's law.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] For disease-causing organisms, there is also a measure known as the median infective dose and dosage.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The median infective dose (ID50) is the number of organisms received by a person or test animal qualified by the route of administration (e.g., 1,200 org/man per oral).
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Because of the difficulties in counting actual organisms in a dose, infective doses may be expressed in terms of biological assay, such as the number of LD50s to some test animal.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] In biological warfare infective dosage is the number of infective doses per cubic metre of air times the number of minutes of exposure (e.g., ICt50 is 100 medium doses - min/m3).
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] As a measure of toxicity, LD50 is somewhat unreliable and results may vary greatly between testing facilities due to factors such as the genetic characteristics of the sample population, animal species tested, environmental factors and mode of administration.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] There can be wide variability between species as well; what is relatively safe for rats may very well be extremely toxic for humans (*cf.* paracetamol toxicity), and vice versa.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] For example, chocolate, comparatively harmless to humans, is known to be toxic to many animals.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] When used to test venom from venomous creatures, such as snakes, LD50 results may be misleading due to the physiological differences between mice, rats, and humans.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Many venomous snakes are specialized predators on mice, and their venom may be adapted specifically to incapacitate mice; and mongooses may be exceptionally resistant.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] While most mammals have a very similar physiology, LD50 results may or may not have equal bearing upon every mammal species, such as humans, etc.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Note: Comparing substances (especially drugs) to each other by LD50 can be misleading in many cases due (in part) to differences in effective dose (ED50).
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Therefore, it is more useful to compare such substances by therapeutic index, which is simply the ratio of LD50 to ED50.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The following examples are listed in reference to LD50 values, in descending order, and accompanied by LC50 values, {bracketed}, when appropriate.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The botulinum toxin as the most toxic substance known has an LD50 value of 1 ng/kg, while the most non-toxic substance water has an LD50 value of more than 90 g/kg; a difference of about 1 in 100 billion, or 11 orders of magnitude.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] As with all measured values that differ by many orders of magnitude, a logarithmic view is advisable.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Well-known examples are the indication of the earthquake strength using magnitude scales, the pH value, as a measure for the acidic or basic character of an aqueous solution or of loudness in decibels.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] In this case, the negative decimal logarithm of the LD50 values, which is standardized in kg per kg body weight, is considered −log10(LD50).
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The dimensionless value found can be entered in a toxin scale.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] Water as the baseline substance is nearly 1 in the negative logarithmic toxin scale.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] A number of procedures have been defined to derive the LD50.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The earliest was the 1927 "conventional" procedure by Trevan, which requires 40 or more animals.
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The fixed-dose procedure, proposed in 1984, estimates a level of toxicity by feeding at defined doses and looking for signs of toxicity (without requiring death).
[src:toxicology/median-lethal-dose] The up-and-down procedure, proposed in 1985, yields an LD50 value while dosing only one animal at a time.
[src:toxicology/poison] In science, a **poison** is any chemical substance that is harmful or lethal to a living organism.
[src:toxicology/poison] The term of poison is used in a wide range of scientific fields and industries, where it is often specifically defined.
[src:toxicology/poison] It may also be applied colloquially or figuratively, with a broad sense.
[src:toxicology/poison] The symptoms and effects of poisoning in humans can mimic those of other medical conditions and vary depending on the type of poison and the system of the body affected.
[src:toxicology/poison] Common symptoms include alterations in consciousness, abnormal body temperature, irregular heart rate, and changes in respiration.
[src:toxicology/poison] The severity and specific presentation of symptoms often depend on the nature and dose of the poison involved.
[src:toxicology/poison] Certain poisons, particularly caustic or irritating substances, can cause direct injury to mucous membranes in the mouth, throat, gastrointestinal tract, and lungs.
[src:toxicology/poison] These injuries may result in symptoms such as pain, coughing, vomiting, and shortness of breath.
[src:toxicology/poison] The term **poisoning** refers to the harmful physiological effects that result from the exposure to a toxic substance, typically through ingestion, inhalation, injection, or skin absorption.
[src:toxicology/poison] It is derived from the word *poison* and is commonly used in medical, biochemical, and toxicological contexts to describe adverse interactions between a substance and a living organism.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poisoning is sometimes used as a method of self-harm and of suicide, particularly in cases of intentional **self-poisoning** among individuals experiencing suicidal ideation.
[src:toxicology/poison] According to *Time Magazine*, self-poisoning is one of the leading methods of suicide attempts among adolescents, and has been identified as the third-leading cause of suicide-related deaths in this age group.
[src:toxicology/poison] A study published in the *Journal of Pediatrics* found that suicide attempts by poisoning among individuals under the age of 19 doubled between 2000 and 2018, increasing from nearly 40,000 cases to almost 80,000.
[src:toxicology/poison] During the COVID-19 lockdowns, reports indicated a 37% increase in cases of deliberate self-poisoning among adolescent girls.
[src:toxicology/poison] In biology, a poison is a chemical substance causing death, injury or harm to organisms or their parts.
[src:toxicology/poison] In medicine, poisons are a kind of toxin that are delivered passively, not actively.
[src:toxicology/poison] In industry the term may be negative, something to be removed to make a thing safe, or positive, an agent to limit unwanted pests.
[src:toxicology/poison] In ecological terms, poisons introduced into the environment can later cause unwanted effects elsewhere, or in other parts of the food chain.
[src:toxicology/poison] The word poison was first recorded in English around the year 1200, meaning "a deadly potion or substance".
[src:toxicology/poison] It derives from the Old French *poison* or *puison* (12th century; Modern French: *poison*), originally meaning "a drink", particularly a medicinal one.
[src:toxicology/poison] By the 14th century, the term had come to signify "a (magic) potion" or "poisonous drink".
[src:toxicology/poison] These uses trace back to the Latin word *potionem* (nominative: *potio*), meaning "a drinking" or "a drink", and more specifically "a poisonous drink", as seen in the writings of Cicero.
[src:toxicology/poison] The Latin root comes from the verb *potare*, meaning "to drink".
[src:toxicology/poison] The use of "poison" as an adjective in the form "poisonous" dates back to the 1520s.
[src:toxicology/poison] The practice of using "poison" in combination with plant names began in the 18th century.
[src:toxicology/poison] For example, the term **poison oak** was first recorded in 1743, and **poison ivy** appeared in usage by 1784.
[src:toxicology/poison] The expression **poison gas** was first used during World War I in 1915.
[src:toxicology/poison] The term poison is often used colloquially to describe any harmful substance, especially corrosive substances, carcinogens, mutagens, teratogens, and harmful pollutants.
[src:toxicology/poison] In everyday language, it is sometimes used to exaggerate the perceived danger of certain chemicals.
[src:toxicology/poison] The 16th-century physician Paracelsus (1493–1541), regarded as the father of toxicology, famously stated: "Everything is poison, there is poison in everything.
[src:toxicology/poison] Only the dose makes a thing not a poison." (See: LD50).
[src:toxicology/poison] The term is also used in a figurative sense—for example: "His brother's presence poisoned the atmosphere at the party." In contrast, legal definitions of "poison" tend to be narrower.
[src:toxicology/poison] Some substances that are not legally required to carry a "poison" label may still cause medical conditions associated with poisoning.
[src:toxicology/poison] Some poisons are also classified as **toxins**, which are toxic substances produced by living organisms.
[src:toxicology/poison] Examples include bacterial proteins responsible for conditions such as tetanus and botulism.
[src:toxicology/poison] While a distinction exists between "poison" and "toxin", the terms are often used interchangeably, even in scientific contexts.
[src:toxicology/poison] Related adjectives include *toxic* and *poisonous*, which are generally considered synonymous.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poisonous substances introduced into the body by sting or bite are known as **venoms**.
[src:toxicology/poison] In everyday usage, a **poisonous organism** is one that causes harm when ingested or touched, while a **venomous organism** uses venom actively to incapacitate prey or deter predators.
[src:toxicology/poison] Although rare, some organisms may be both poisonous and venomous.
[src:toxicology/poison] All living organisms produce substances to defend themselves from being eaten.
[src:toxicology/poison] However, the term "poison" typically refers to substances that are toxic to humans.
[src:toxicology/poison] Substances that are toxic primarily to pathogens and not to humans are generally classified as **antibiotics**.
[src:toxicology/poison] For instance, *Penicillium chrysogenum* produces compounds toxic to bacteria, but not to humans, making them effective as antibacterial drugs.
[src:toxicology/poison] Similarly, human antimicrobial peptides, which are toxic to viruses, fungi, bacteria, and cancerous cells; are considered part of the innate immune system.
[src:toxicology/poison] In nuclear physics, the term **nuclear poison** refers to a substance that absorbs neutrons and interferes with a nuclear reaction.
[src:toxicology/poison] Substances classified as environmentally hazardous are not always poisonous, and vice versa.
[src:toxicology/poison] For example, wastewater from food processing, such as potato juice or milk; can be environmentally damaging by depleting oxygen in aquatic ecosystems (leading to eutrophication), but it poses no direct toxic threat to humans and is not considered a poison.
[src:toxicology/poison] From a biological standpoint, virtually any substance can be toxic in sufficient quantity.
[src:toxicology/poison] Even something as essential as water can be fatal when consumed in excessive amounts; a condition known as **water intoxication**.
[src:toxicology/poison] Many drugs used in medicine, such as fentanyl, have a median lethal dose (LD50) only slightly higher than their effective dose (ED50), highlighting the thin margin between therapeutic benefit and toxicity.
[src:toxicology/poison] Some classification systems differentiate between lethal substances with therapeutic value and those without.
[src:toxicology/poison] In broad metaphorical (colloquial) usage of the term, "poison" may refer to anything deemed harmful.
[src:toxicology/poison] In biology, poisons are substances that can cause death, injury, or harm to organs, tissues, cells, and DNA usually by chemical reactions or other activity on the molecular scale, when an organism is exposed to a sufficient quantity.
[src:toxicology/poison] Medicinal fields (particularly veterinary medicine) and zoology often distinguish poisons from *toxins* and *venoms*.
[src:toxicology/poison] Both poisons and venoms are toxins, which are toxicants produced by organisms in nature.
[src:toxicology/poison] The difference between venom and poison is the delivery method of the toxin.
[src:toxicology/poison] Venoms are toxins that are actively delivered by being injected via a bite or sting through a *venom apparatus*, such as fangs or a stinger, in a process called envenomation, whereas poisons are toxins that are passively delivered by being swallowed, inhaled, or absorbed through the skin.
[src:toxicology/poison] *Unantidoteable* refers to toxins that cannot be neutralized by modern medical technology, regardless of their type.
[src:toxicology/poison] Industry, agriculture, and other sectors employ many poisonous substances, usually for reasons other than their toxicity to humans.
[src:toxicology/poison] Examples include medicines (e.g. anthelmintics used on chickens), solvents (e.g. rubbing alcohol, turpentine), cleaners (e.g. bleach, ammonia), coatings (e.g. arsenic wallpaper), and feedstocks.
[src:toxicology/poison] The toxicity itself sometimes has economic value, when it serves agricultural purposes such as weed control and pest control.
[src:toxicology/poison] Most poisonous industrial compounds have associated material safety data sheets and are classified as hazardous substances.
[src:toxicology/poison] Hazardous substances are subject to extensive regulation on production, procurement, and use in overlapping domains of occupational safety and health, public health, drinking water quality standards, air pollution, and environmental protection.
[src:toxicology/poison] Due to the mechanics of molecular diffusion, many poisonous compounds rapidly diffuse into biological tissues, air, water, or soil on a molecular scale.
[src:toxicology/poison] By the principle of entropy, chemical contamination is typically costly or infeasible to reverse, unless specific chelating agents or micro-filtration processes are available.
[src:toxicology/poison] Chelating agents are often broader in scope than the acute target, and therefore their ingestion necessitates careful medical or veterinarian supervision.
[src:toxicology/poison] Pesticides are one group of substances whose prime purpose is their toxicity to various insects and other animals deemed to be pests (e.g., rats and cockroaches).
[src:toxicology/poison] Natural pesticides have been used for this purpose for thousands of years (e.g. concentrated table salt is toxic to many slugs and snails).
[src:toxicology/poison] Bioaccumulation of chemically-prepared agricultural insecticides is a matter of concern for the many species, especially birds, which consume insects as a primary food source.
[src:toxicology/poison] Apart from food, many poisons readily enter the body through the skin and lungs.
[src:toxicology/poison] Hydrofluoric acid is a notorious contact poison, in addition to its corrosive damage.
[src:toxicology/poison] Naturally occurring sour gas is a fast-acting atmospheric poison, which can be released by volcanic activity or drilling rigs.
[src:toxicology/poison] Plant-based contact irritants, such as that possessed by poison ivy, are often classed as allergens rather than poisons; the effect of an allergen being not a poison as such, but to turn the body's natural defenses against itself.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poison can also enter the body through faulty medical implants, or by injection (which is the basis of lethal injection in the context of capital punishment).
[src:toxicology/poison] In 2013, 3.3 million cases of unintentional human poisonings occurred.
[src:toxicology/poison] This resulted in 98,000 deaths worldwide, down from 120,000 deaths in 1990.
[src:toxicology/poison] In modern society, cases of suspicious death elicit the attention of the Coroner's office and forensic investigators.
[src:toxicology/poison] Of increasing concern since the isolation of natural radium by Marie and Pierre Curie in 1898—and the subsequent advent of nuclear physics and nuclear technologies—are radiological poisons.
[src:toxicology/poison] These are associated with ionizing radiation, a mode of toxicity quite distinct from chemically active poisons.
[src:toxicology/poison] In mammals, chemical poisons are often passed from mother to offspring through the placenta during gestation, or through breast milk during nursing.
[src:toxicology/poison] In contrast, radiological damage can be passed from mother or father to offspring through genetic mutation, which—if not fatal in miscarriage or childhood, or a direct cause of infertility—can then be passed along again to a subsequent generation.
[src:toxicology/poison] Atmospheric radon is a natural radiological poison of increasing impact since humans moved from hunter-gatherer lifestyles and cave dwelling to increasingly enclosed structures able to contain radon in dangerous concentrations.
[src:toxicology/poison] The 2006 poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko was a notable use of radiological assassination, presumably meant to evade the normal investigation of chemical poisons.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poisons widely dispersed into the environment are known as pollution.
[src:toxicology/poison] The scientific disciplines of ecology and environmental resource management study the environmental life cycle of toxic compounds and their complex, diffuse, and highly interrelated effects.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poisoning can be either acute or chronic, and caused by a variety of natural or synthetic substances.
[src:toxicology/poison] Substances that destroy tissue but do not absorb, such as lye, are classified as corrosives rather than poisons.
[src:toxicology/poison] Acute poisoning is exposure to a poison on one occasion or during a short period of time.
[src:toxicology/poison] Symptoms develop in close relation to the exposure.
[src:toxicology/poison] Absorption of a poison is necessary for systemic poisoning.
[src:toxicology/poison] Furthermore, many common household medications are not labeled with skull and crossbones, although they can cause severe illness or even death.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poisoning can be caused by excessive consumption of generally safe substances, as in the case of water intoxication.
[src:toxicology/poison] Agents that act on the nervous system can paralyze in seconds or less, and include both biologically derived neurotoxins and so-called nerve gases, which may be synthesized for warfare or industry.
[src:toxicology/poison] Inhaled or ingested cyanide, used as a method of execution in gas chambers, or as a suicide method, almost instantly starves the body of energy by inhibiting the enzymes in mitochondria that make ATP.
[src:toxicology/poison] Intravenous injection of an unnaturally high concentration of potassium chloride, such as in the execution of prisoners in parts of the United States, quickly stops the heart by eliminating the cell potential necessary for muscle contraction.
[src:toxicology/poison] Most biocides, including pesticides, are created to act as acute poisons to target organisms, although acute or less observable chronic poisoning can also occur in non-target organisms (secondary poisoning), including the humans who apply the biocides and other beneficial organisms.
[src:toxicology/poison] For example, the herbicide 2,4-D imitates the action of a plant hormone, which makes its lethal toxicity specific to plants.
[src:toxicology/poison] Indeed, 2,4-D is not a poison, but classified as "harmful" (EU).
[src:toxicology/poison] Many substances regarded as poisons are toxic only indirectly, by toxication.
[src:toxicology/poison] An example is "wood alcohol" or methanol, which is not poisonous itself, but is chemically converted to toxic formaldehyde and formic acid in the liver.
[src:toxicology/poison] Many drug molecules are made toxic in the liver, and the genetic variability of certain liver enzymes makes the toxicity of many compounds differ between individuals.
[src:toxicology/poison] Exposure to radioactive substances can produce radiation poisoning, an unrelated phenomenon.
[src:toxicology/poison] Two common cases of acute natural poisoning are theobromine poisoning of dogs and cats, and mushroom poisoning in humans.
[src:toxicology/poison] Dogs and cats are not natural herbivores, but a chemical defense developed by *Theobroma cacao* can be incidentally fatal nevertheless.
[src:toxicology/poison] Many omnivores, including humans, readily consume edible fungi, and thus many fungi have evolved to become decisively inedible, in this case as a direct defense.
[src:toxicology/poison] Chronic poisoning is long-term repeated or continuous exposure to a poison where symptoms do not occur immediately or after each exposure.
[src:toxicology/poison] The person gradually becomes ill, or becomes ill after a long latent period.
[src:toxicology/poison] Chronic poisoning most commonly occurs following exposure to poisons that bioaccumulate, or are biomagnified, such as mercury, gadolinium, and lead.
[src:toxicology/poison] There were approximately 727,500 emergency department visits in the United States involving poisonings—3.3% of all injury-related encounters.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poisonous compounds may be useful either for their toxicity, or, more often, because of another chemical property, such as specific chemical reactivity.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poisons are widely used in industry and agriculture, as chemical reagents, solvents or complexing reagents, e.g. carbon monoxide, methanol and sodium cyanide, respectively.
[src:toxicology/poison] They are less common in household use, with occasional exceptions such as ammonia and methanol.
[src:toxicology/poison] For instance, phosgene is a highly reactive nucleophile acceptor, which makes it an excellent reagent for polymerizing diols and diamines to produce polycarbonate and polyurethane plastics.
[src:toxicology/poison] For this use, millions of tons are produced annually.
[src:toxicology/poison] However, the same reactivity makes it also highly reactive towards proteins in human tissue and thus highly toxic.
[src:toxicology/poison] In fact, phosgene has been used as a chemical weapon.
[src:toxicology/poison] It can be contrasted with mustard gas, which has only been produced for chemical weapons uses, as it has no particular industrial use.
[src:toxicology/poison] Biocides need not be poisonous to humans, because they can target metabolic pathways absent in humans, leaving only incidental toxicity.
[src:toxicology/poison] For instance, the herbicide 2,4-dichlorophenoxyacetic acid is a mimic of a plant growth hormone, which causes uncontrollable growth leading to the death of the plant.
[src:toxicology/poison] Humans and animals, lacking this hormone and its receptor, are unaffected by this, and need to ingest relatively large doses before any toxicity appears.
[src:toxicology/poison] Human toxicity is, however, hard to avoid with pesticides targeting mammals, such as rodenticides.
[src:toxicology/poison] The risk from toxicity is also distinct from toxicity itself.
[src:toxicology/poison] For instance, the preservative thiomersal used in vaccines is toxic, but the quantity administered in a single shot is negligible.
[src:toxicology/poison] Throughout human history, intentional application of poison has been used as a method of murder, pest-control, suicide, and execution.
[src:toxicology/poison] As a method of execution, poison has been ingested, as the ancient Athenians did (see Socrates), inhaled, as with carbon monoxide or hydrogen cyanide (see gas chamber), injected (see lethal injection), or even as an enema.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poison's lethal effect can be combined with its allegedly magical powers; an example is the Chinese *gu* poison.
[src:toxicology/poison] Poison was also employed in gunpowder warfare.
[src:toxicology/poison] For example, the 14th-century Chinese text of the *Huolongjing* written by Jiao Yu outlined the use of a poisonous gunpowder mixture to fill cast iron grenade bombs.
[src:toxicology/poison] While arsenic is a naturally occurring environmental poison, its artificial concentrate was once nicknamed inheritance powder.
[src:toxicology/poison] In Medieval Europe, it was common for monarchs to employ personal food tasters to thwart royal assassination, in the dawning age of the Apothecary.
[src:toxicology/poison] The term **poison** is also used in a figurative sense.
[src:toxicology/poison] The slang sense of alcoholic drink is first attested 1805, American English (e.g., a bartender might ask a customer "what's your poison?" or "Pick your poison").
[src:toxicology/poison] Figurative use of the term dates from the late 15th century.
[src:toxicology/poison] Figuratively referring to persons as poison dates from 1910.
[src:toxicology/poison] The figurative term poison pen letter became well known in 1913 by a notorious criminal case in Pennsylvania, U.S.; the phrase dates to 1898.
[src:toxicology/poison] Despite the plants of the Toxicodendron family having the names poison ivy and poison oak, the oil urushiol they produce is not a true poison and is actually an allergen, which 15% of people are resistant to.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] A central concept of toxicology is that the effects of a toxicant are dose-dependent; even water can lead to water intoxication when taken in too high a dose, whereas for even a very toxic substance such as snake venom there is a dose below which there is no detectable toxic effect.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Toxicity is species-specific, making cross-species analysis problematic.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Newer paradigms and metrics are evolving to bypass animal testing, while maintaining the concept of toxicity endpoints.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Humans have a deeply rooted history of not only being aware of toxicity, but also taking advantage of it as a tool.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Archaeologists studying bone arrows from caves of Southern Africa have noted the likelihood that some, aging 72,000 to 80,000 years old, were dipped in specially prepared poisons to increase their lethality.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Although scientific instrumentation limitations make it difficult to prove concretely, archaeologists hypothesize the practice of making poison arrows was widespread in cultures as early as the Paleolithic era.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] The San people of Southern Africa have managed to preserve this practice into the modern era, with the knowledge base to form complex mixtures from poisonous beetles and plant derived extracts, yielding an arrow-tip product with a shelf life beyond several months to a year.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] In general, there are five types of toxicities: chemical, biological, physical, radioactive and behavioural.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Disease-causing microorganisms and parasites are toxic in a broad sense but are generally called pathogens rather than toxicants.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] The biological toxicity of pathogens can be difficult to measure because the threshold dose may be a single organism.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Theoretically one virus, bacterium or worm can reproduce to cause a serious infection.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] If a host has an intact immune system, the inherent toxicity of the organism is balanced by the host's response; the effective toxicity is then a combination.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] In some cases, e.g. cholera toxin, the disease is chiefly caused by a nonliving substance secreted by the organism, rather than the organism itself.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Such nonliving biological toxicants are generally called toxins if produced by a microorganism, plant, or fungus, and venoms if produced by an animal.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Physical toxicants are substances that, due to their physical nature, interfere with biological processes.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Examples include coal dust, asbestos fibres or finely divided silicon dioxide, all of which can ultimately be fatal if inhaled.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Corrosive chemicals possess physical toxicity because they destroy tissues, but are not directly poisonous unless they interfere directly with biological activity.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Water can act as a physical toxicant if taken in extremely high doses because the concentration of vital ions decreases dramatically with too much water in the body.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Asphyxiant gases can be considered physical toxicants because they act by displacing oxygen in the environment but they are inert, not chemically toxic gases.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Radiation can have a toxic effect on organisms.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Behavioral toxicity refers to the undesirable effects of essentially therapeutic levels of medication clinically indicated for a given disorder.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] These undesirable effects include anticholinergic effects, alpha-adrenergic blockade, and dopaminergic effects, among others.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Toxicity can be measured by its effects on the target (organism, organ, tissue or cell).
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Because individuals typically have different levels of response to the same dose of a toxic substance, a population-level measure of toxicity is often used which relates the probabilities of an outcome for a given individual in a population.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] When such data does not exist, estimates are made by comparison to known similar toxic things, or to similar exposures in similar organisms.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Then, "safety factors" are added to account for uncertainties in data and evaluation processes.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Similarly, an extra protection factor may be used for individuals believed to be more susceptible to toxic effects such as in pregnancy or with certain diseases.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Or, a newly synthesized and previously unstudied chemical that is believed to be very similar in effect to another compound could be assigned an additional protection factor of 10 to account for possible differences in effects that are probably much smaller.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] This approach is very approximate, but such protection factors are deliberately very conservative, and the method has been found to be useful in a wide variety of applications.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Assessing all aspects of the toxicity of cancer-causing agents involves additional issues, since it is not certain if there is a minimal effective dose for carcinogens, or whether the risk is just too small to see.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] In addition, it is possible that a single cell transformed into a cancer cell is all it takes to develop the full effect (the "one hit" theory).
[src:toxicology/toxicity] It is more difficult to determine the toxicity of chemical mixtures than a pure chemical because each component displays its own toxicity, and components may interact to produce enhanced or diminished effects.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Common mixtures include gasoline, cigarette smoke, and industrial waste.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Even more complex are situations with more than one type of toxic entity, such as the discharge from a malfunctioning sewage treatment plant, with both chemical and biological agents.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] The preclinical toxicity testing on various biological systems reveals the species-, organ- and dose-specific toxic effects of an investigational product.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] The toxicity of substances can be observed by (a) studying the accidental exposures to a substance (b) in vitro studies using cells/ cell lines (c) in vivo exposure on experimental animals.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Toxicity tests are mostly used to examine specific adverse events or specific endpoints such as cancer, cardiotoxicity, and skin/eye irritation.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Toxicity testing also helps calculate the No Observed Adverse Effect Level (NOAEL) dose and is helpful for clinical studies.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] For substances to be regulated and handled appropriately they must be properly classified and labelled.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Classification is determined by approved testing measures or calculations and has determined cut-off levels set by governments and scientists (for example, no-observed-adverse-effect levels, threshold limit values, and tolerable daily intake levels).
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Pesticides provide the example of well-established toxicity class systems and toxicity labels.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] While currently many countries have different regulations regarding the types of tests, numbers of tests and cut-off levels, the implementation of the Globally Harmonized System has begun unifying these countries.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Global classification looks at three areas: physical hazards (explosions and pyrotechnics), health hazards and environmental hazards.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] The types of toxicities where substances may cause lethality to the entire body, lethality to specific organs, major/minor damage, or cause cancer.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] These are globally accepted definitions of what toxicity is.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Anything falling outside of the definition cannot be classified as that type of toxicant.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Acute toxicity looks at lethal effects following oral, dermal or inhalation exposure.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] It is split into five categories of severity where Category 1 requires the least amount of exposure to be lethal and Category 5 requires the most exposure to be lethal.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] The table below shows the upper limits for each category.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Note: The undefined values are expected to be roughly equivalent to the category 5 values for oral and dermal administration.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Skin corrosion and irritation are determined through a skin patch test analysis, similar to an allergic inflammation patch test.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] This examines the severity of the damage done; when it is incurred and how long it remains; whether it is reversible and how many test subjects were affected.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Skin corrosion from a substance must penetrate through the epidermis into the dermis within four hours of application and must not reverse the damage within 14 days.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Skin irritation shows damage less severe than corrosion if: the damage occurs within 72 hours of application; or for three consecutive days after application within a 14-day period; or causes inflammation which lasts for 14 days in two test subjects.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Mild skin irritation is minor damage (less severe than irritation) within 72 hours of application or for three consecutive days after application.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Serious eye damage involves tissue damage or degradation of vision which does not fully reverse in 21 days.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Eye irritation involves changes to the eye which do fully reverse within 21 days.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] An environmental hazard can be defined as any condition, process, or state adversely affecting the environment.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] These hazards can be physical or chemical, and present in air, water, and/or soil.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] These conditions can cause extensive harm to humans and other organisms within an ecosystem.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] The EPA maintains a list of priority pollutants for testing and regulation.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Workers in various occupations may be at a greater level of risk for several types of toxicity, including neurotoxicity.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] The expression "Mad as a hatter" and the "Mad Hatter" of the book Alice in Wonderland derive from the known occupational toxicity of hatters who used a toxic chemical for controlling the shape of hats.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Exposure to chemicals in the workplace environment may be required for evaluation by industrial hygiene professionals.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Hazards in the arts have been an issue for artists for centuries, even though the toxicity of their tools, methods, and materials was not always adequately realized.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Lead and cadmium, among other toxic elements, were often incorporated into the names of artist's oil paints and pigments, for example, "lead white" and "cadmium red".
[src:toxicology/toxicity] 20th-century printmakers and other artists began to be aware of the toxic substances, toxic techniques, and toxic fumes in glues, painting mediums, pigments, and solvents, many of which in their labelling gave no indication of their toxicity.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] An example was the use of xylol for cleaning silk screens.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Painters began to notice the dangers of breathing painting mediums and thinners such as turpentine.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] There are many environmental health mapping tools.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] TOXMAP is a resource funded by the US Federal Government.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] TOXMAP's chemical and environmental health information is taken from NLM's Toxicology Data Network (TOXNET) and PubMed, and from other authoritative sources.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Aquatic toxicity testing subjects key indicator species of fish or crustacea to certain concentrations of a substance in their environment to determine the lethality level.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Fish are exposed for 96 hours while crustacea are exposed for 48 hours.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] While GHS does not define toxicity past 100 mg/L, the EPA currently lists aquatic toxicity as "practically non-toxic" in concentrations greater than 100 ppm.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Note: A category 4 is established for chronic exposure, but simply contains any toxic substance which is mostly insoluble, or has no data for acute toxicity.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Several of the terms used to describe these factors have been included here.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] A single exposure to a toxic substance which may result in severe biological harm or death; acute exposures are usually characterized as lasting no longer than a day.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Continuous exposure to a toxicant over an extended period of time, often measured in months or years; it can cause irreversible side effects.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] Considering the limitations of the dose-response concept, a novel Abstract Drug Toxicity Index (DTI) has been proposed recently.
[src:toxicology/toxicity] DTI redefines drug toxicity, identifies hepatotoxic drugs, gives mechanistic insights, predicts clinical outcomes and has potential as a screening tool.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] It is an application of pharmacokinetics to determine the relationship between the systemic exposure of a compound and its toxicity.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] It is used primarily for establishing relationships between exposures in toxicology experiments in animals and the corresponding exposures in humans.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] However, it can also be used in environmental risk assessments in order to determine the potential effects of releasing chemicals into the environment.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] In order to quantify toxic effects, toxicokinetics can be combined with toxicodynamics.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] Such toxicokinetic-toxicodynamic (TKTD) models are used in ecotoxicology.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] Four potential processes exist for a chemical interacting with an animal: absorption, distribution, metabolism and excretion (ADME).
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] Absorption describes the entrance of the chemical into the body, and can occur through the air, water, food, or soil.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] Once a chemical is inside a body, it can be distributed to other areas of the body through diffusion or other biological processes.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] At this point, the chemical may undergo metabolism and be biotransformed into other chemicals (metabolites).
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] These metabolites can be less or more toxic than the parent compound.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] After this potential biotransformation occurs, the metabolites may leave the body, be transformed into other compounds, or continue to be stored in the body compartments.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] A well designed toxicokinetic study may involve several different strategies and depends on the scientific question to be answered.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] Controlled acute and repeated toxicokinetic animal studies are useful to identify a chemical's biological persistence, tissue and whole body half-life, and its potential to bioaccumulate.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] Toxicokinetic profiles can change with increasing exposure duration or dose.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] Real world environmental exposures generally occur as low level mixtures, such as from air, water, food, or tobacco products.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] Mixture effects may differ from individual chemical toxicokinetic profiles because of chemical interactions, synergistic, or competitive processes.
[src:toxicology/toxicokinetics] For other reasons, it is equally important to characterize the toxicokinetics of individual chemicals constituents found in mixtures as information on behavior or fate of the individual chemical can help explain environmental, human, and wildlife biomonitoring studies.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The word *toxicology* (/ˌtɒksɪˈkɒlədʒi/) is a neoclassical compound from Neo-Latin, first attested c.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] 1799, from the combining forms *toxico-* + *-logy*, which in turn come from the Ancient Greek words τοξικός *toxikos*, "poisonous", and λόγος *logos*, "subject matter").
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Unlike many civilizations, records of Egyptian knowledge and use of poisons can only be dated back to approximately 300 BC.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] However, it is believed that the earliest known Egyptian pharaoh, Menes, studied the properties of poisonous plants and venoms, according to early records.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The Egyptians are also thought to have come into knowledge about elements such as antimony, copper, crude arsenic, lead, opium, and mandrake (among others) which are mentioned in papyri.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] They carefully documented venomous snakes and scorpions, their effects, and treatments, using controlled herbal poisons in medicine, and are also thought to have been the first to master distillation and extract poison from apricot kernels.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The Kalpasthāna is a section of the Suśrutasaṃhitā, an ancient Sanskrit medical compendium composed before c.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] 300 CE, with portions possibly dating to the fourth century BCE.It is devoted to the study of plant and animal poisons, including their classification, identification, and treatment.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The *Kalpasthāna* was influential on many later Sanskrit medical works and was translated into Arabic and other languages, influencing South East Asia, the Middle East, Tibet and eventually Europe.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Dioscorides, a Greek physician in the court of the Roman emperor Nero, made an early attempt to classify plants according to their toxic and therapeutic effect.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] A work attributed to the 10th century author Ibn Wahshiyya called the *Book on Poisons* describes various toxic substances and poisonous recipes that can be made using magic.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] In the 12th century, Jewish physician **Maimonides** wrote *Kitāb al-Sumūm wa-l-Mutaḥarriz min al-Adwiya al-Qattāla* ("Book on Poisons and the One Who Guards Against Deadly Drugs"), which discussed the treatment of poisoning.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] A 14th century Kannada poetic work attributed to the Jain prince Mangarasa, *Khagendra Mani Darpana*, describes several poisonous plants.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The late medieval philosopher Pietro d'Abano compiled a treatise on venoms and poisons drawing on earlier Greek sources, particularly works attributed to Dioscorides such as On Venoms and On Poisons.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] This work reflects an early engagement with Greek scientific traditions and has been viewed as a precursor to the later revival of Greek science associated with the Renaissance.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The 16th-century Swiss physician Paracelsus is considered "the father" of modern toxicology, based on his rigorous approach to understanding the effects of substances on the body.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Mathieu Orfila is also considered the modern father of toxicology, having given the subject its first formal treatment in 1813 in his *Traité des poisons*, also called *Toxicologie générale*.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] In 1850, Jean Stas became the first person to successfully isolate plant poisons from human tissue.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] This allowed him to identify the use of nicotine as a poison in the Bocarmé murder case, providing the evidence needed to convict the Belgian Count Hippolyte Visart de Bocarmé of killing his brother-in-law.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] In the modern era, regulatory oversight of toxicology has shifted to specialized governmental and international bodies, including the U.S.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Food and Drug Administration (FDA), the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), and the World Health Organization (WHO), which enforce standardized protocols to assess chemical risks in food, drugs, and the environment.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Building on Paracelsus's foundational dose-response principle, these agencies guide evidence-based safety evaluations through tiered toxicity studies and data interpretation.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The FDA's Redbook 2000 exemplifies this continued evolution, serving as a pivotal guidance document for toxicological principles in assessing food additives and ingredients, ensuring public health protections aligned with contemporary scientific rigor.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The goal of toxicity assessment is to identify adverse effects of a substance.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Adverse effects depend on two main factors: i) routes of exposure (oral, inhalation, or dermal) and ii) dose (duration and concentration of exposure).
[src:toxicology/toxicology] To explore dose, substances are tested in both acute and chronic models.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Generally, different sets of experiments are conducted to determine whether a substance causes cancer and to examine other forms of toxicity.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Evidence-based toxicology has the potential to address concerns in the toxicological community about the limitations of current approaches to assessing the state of the science.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] These include concerns related to transparency in decision-making, synthesis of different types of evidence, and the assessment of bias and credibility.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Evidence-based toxicology has its roots in the larger movement towards evidence-based practices.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Toxicity experiments may be conducted *in vivo* (using the whole animal) or *in vitro* (testing on isolated cells or tissues), or *in silico* (in a computer simulation).
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The classic experimental tool of toxicology is testing on non-human animals.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Examples of model organisms are *Galleria mellonella,* which can replace small mammals, Zebrafish (*Danio rerio*), which allow for the study of toxicology in a lower order vertebrate *in vivo* and *Caenorhabditis elegans*.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] As of 2014, such animal testing provides information that is not available by other means about how substances function in a living organism.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The use of non-human animals for toxicology testing is opposed by some organisations for reasons of animal welfare, and it has been restricted or banned under some circumstances in certain regions, such as the testing of cosmetics in the European Union.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] While testing in animal models remains as a method of estimating human effects, there are both ethical and technical concerns with animal testing.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The historical development of alternative testing methods in toxicology has been published by Balls.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] This work requires expert knowledge in molecular modeling and statistics together with expert judgment in chemistry, biology and toxicology.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] In 2007 the American NGO National Academy of Sciences published a report called "Toxicity Testing in the 21st Century: A Vision and a Strategy" which opened with a statement: "Change often involves a pivotal event that builds on previous history and opens the door to a new era.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Pivotal events in science include the discovery of penicillin, the elucidation of the DNA double helix, and the development of computers. ...
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Toxicity testing is approaching such a scientific pivot point.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] It is poised to take advantage of the revolutions in biology and biotechnology.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] In some cases shifts away from animal studies have been mandated by law or regulation; the European Union (EU) prohibited use of animal testing for cosmetics in 2013.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Most chemicals display a classic dose response curve – at a low dose (below a threshold), no effect is observed.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Some show a phenomenon known as sufficient challenge – a small exposure produces animals that "grow more rapidly, have better general appearance and coat quality, have fewer tumors, and live longer than the control animals".
[src:toxicology/toxicology] A few chemicals have no well-defined safe level of exposure.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Some chemicals are subject to bioaccumulation as they are stored in rather than being excreted from the body; these also receive special consideration.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Several measures are commonly used to describe toxic dosages according to the degree of effect on an organism or a population, and some are specifically defined by various laws or organizational usage.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Medical toxicology is the discipline that requires physician status (MD or DO degree plus specialty education and experience).
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Clinical toxicology is the discipline that can be practiced not only by physicians but also other health professionals with a master's degree in clinical toxicology: physician extenders (physician assistants, nurse practitioners), nurses, pharmacists, and allied health professionals.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Forensic toxicology is the discipline that makes use of toxicology and other disciplines such as analytical chemistry, pharmacology and clinical chemistry to aid medical or legal investigation of death, poisoning, and drug use.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The primary concern for forensic toxicology is not the legal outcome of the toxicological investigation or the technology utilized, but rather the obtainment and interpretation of results.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Computational toxicology is a discipline that develops mathematical and computer-based models to better understand and predict adverse health effects caused by chemicals, such as environmental pollutants and pharmaceuticals.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Within the *Toxicology in the 21st Century* project, the best predictive models were identified to be Deep Neural Networks, Random Forest, and Support Vector Machines, which can reach the performance of in vitro experiments.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Occupational toxicology is the application of toxicology to chemical hazards in the workplace.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] A **toxicologist** is a scientist or medical personnel who specializes in the study of chemicals to determine if they are harmful to living organisms.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] They may analyze symptoms, mechanisms, treatments and detection of venoms and toxins; especially the poisoning of people.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] There are several types of toxicologist including medical, academic and non-profit.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] To work as a toxicologist one should obtain a degree in toxicology or a related degree like biology, chemistry, pharmacology or biochemistry.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Bachelor's degree programs in toxicology cover the chemical makeup of toxins and their effects on biochemistry, physiology and ecology.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] After introductory life science courses are complete, students typically enroll in labs and apply toxicology principles to research and other studies.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Advanced students delve into specific sectors, like the pharmaceutical industry or law enforcement, which apply methods of toxicology in their work.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The Society of Toxicology (SOT) recommends that undergraduates in postsecondary schools that do not offer a bachelor's degree in toxicology consider attaining a degree in biology or chemistry.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Additionally, the SOT advises aspiring toxicologists to take statistics and mathematics courses, as well as gain laboratory experience through lab courses, student research projects and internships.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] In the USA, Medical Toxicologists complete residency training such as in Emergency Medicine, Pediatrics or Internal Medicine, followed by fellowship in Medical Toxicology and eventual certification by the American College of Medical Toxicology (ACMT).
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Toxicologists perform many different duties including research in the academic, nonprofit and industrial fields, product safety evaluation, consulting, public service and legal regulation.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] In order to research and assess the effects of chemicals, toxicologists perform carefully designed studies and experiments.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] These experiments help identify the specific amount of a chemical that may cause harm and potential risks of being near or using products that contain certain chemicals.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] Research projects may range from assessing the effects of toxic pollutants on the environment to evaluating how the human immune system responds to chemical compounds within pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] While the basic duties of toxicologists are to determine the effects of chemicals on organisms and their surroundings, specific job duties may vary based on industry and employment.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] For example, forensic toxicologists may look for toxic substances in a crime scene, whereas aquatic toxicologists may analyze the toxicity level of water bodies.
[src:toxicology/toxicology] The salary for jobs in toxicology is dependent on several factors, including level of schooling, specialization, experience.
[src:toxicology/toxin] A **toxin** is a naturally occurring poison produced by metabolic activities of living cells or organisms.
[src:toxicology/toxin] They occur especially as proteins, often conjugated.
[src:toxicology/toxin] The term was first used by organic chemist Ludwig Brieger (1849–1919), derived from *toxic*.
[src:toxicology/toxin] Toxins can be small molecules, peptides, or proteins that are capable of causing disease on contact with or absorption by body tissues interacting with biological macromolecules such as enzymes or cellular receptors.
[src:toxicology/toxin] They vary greatly in their toxicity, ranging from usually minor (such as a bee sting) to potentially fatal even at extremely low doses (such as botulinum toxin).
[src:toxicology/toxin] Toxins are often distinguished from other chemical agents strictly based on their biological origin.
[src:toxicology/toxin] Less strict understandings embrace naturally occurring inorganic toxins, such as arsenic.
[src:toxicology/toxin] Other understandings embrace synthetic analogs of naturally occurring organic poisons as toxins, and may or may not embrace naturally occurring inorganic poisons.
[src:toxicology/toxin] It is important to confirm usage if a common understanding is critical.
[src:toxicology/toxin] The term toxicant is preferred when the poison is man-made and therefore artificial.
[src:toxicology/toxin] The human and scientific genetic assembly of a natural-based toxin should be considered a toxin as it is identical to its natural counterpart.
[src:toxicology/toxin] The debate is one of linguistic semantics.
[src:toxicology/toxin] The word toxin does not specify method of delivery (as opposed to venom, a toxin delivered via a bite, sting, etc.).
[src:toxicology/toxin] Poison is a related but broader term that encompasses both toxins and toxicants; poisons may enter the body through any means - typically inhalation, ingestion, or skin absorption.
[src:toxicology/toxin] Toxin, toxicant, and poison are often used interchangeably despite these subtle differences in definition.
[src:toxicology/toxin] The term toxungen has also been proposed to refer to toxins that are delivered onto the body surface of another organism without an accompanying wound.
[src:toxicology/toxin] On a broader scale, toxins may be classified as either exotoxins, excreted by an organism, or endotoxins, which are released mainly when bacteria are lysed.
[src:toxicology/toxin] The term "biotoxin" is sometimes used to explicitly confirm the biological origin as opposed to environmental or anthropogenic origins.
[src:toxicology/toxin] They can also be classified by their source, such as fungal biotoxins, microbial toxins, plant biotoxins, or animal biotoxins.
[src:toxicology/toxin] Toxins produced by microorganisms are important virulence determinants responsible for microbial pathogenicity and/or evasion of the host immune response.
[src:toxicology/toxin] Biotoxins vary greatly in purpose and mechanism, and can be highly complex (the venom of the cone snail can contain over 100 unique peptides, which target specific nerve channels or receptors).
[src:toxicology/toxin] Many living organisms employ toxins offensively or defensively.
[src:toxicology/toxin] A relatively small number of toxins are known to have the potential to cause widespread sickness or casualties.
[src:toxicology/toxin] They are often inexpensive and easily available, and in some cases it is possible to refine them outside the laboratory.
[src:toxicology/toxin] As biotoxins act quickly, and are highly toxic even at low doses, they can be more efficient than chemical agents.
[src:toxicology/toxin] Due to these factors, it is vital to raise awareness of the clinical symptoms of biotoxin poisoning, and to develop effective countermeasures including rapid investigation, response, and treatment.
[src:toxicology/toxin] The term "environmental toxin" can sometimes explicitly include synthetic contaminants such as industrial pollutants and other artificially made toxic substances.
[src:toxicology/toxin] As this contradicts most formal definitions of the term "toxin", it is important to confirm what the researcher means when encountering the term outside of microbiological contexts.
[src:toxicology/toxin] In general, when scientists determine the amount of a substance that may be hazardous for humans, animals and/or the environment they determine the amount of the substance likely to trigger effects and if possible establish a safe level.
[src:toxicology/toxin] In Europe, the European Food Safety Authority produced risk assessments for more than 4,000 substances in over 1,600 scientific opinions and they provide open access summaries of human health, animal health and ecological hazard assessments in their OpenFoodTox database.
[src:toxicology/toxin] The OpenFoodTox database can be used to screen potential new foods for toxicity.
[src:toxicology/toxin] This web site includes links to databases, bibliographies, tutorials, and other scientific and consumer-oriented resources.
[src:toxicology/toxin] TEHIP also is responsible for the Toxicology Data Network (TOXNET), an integrated system of toxicology and environmental health databases that are available free of charge on the web.
[src:toxicology/toxin] TOXMAP is a Geographic Information System (GIS) that is part of TOXNET.
[src:toxicology/toxin] TOXMAP uses maps of the United States to help users visually explore data from the United States Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) Toxics Release Inventory and Superfund Basic Research Programs.
